<doc id="981855" wikidata="Q4380191" url="?curid=981855" title="Blaschke product">
<text>In complex analysis, the Blaschke product is a bounded analytic function in the open unit disc constructed to have zeros at a (finite or infinite) sequence of prescribed complex numbers

:formula_1

inside the unit disc, with the property that the magnitude of the function is constant along the boundary of the disc.
Blaschke products were introduced by . They are related to Hardy spaces.

==Definition==

A sequence of points formula_2 inside the unit disk is said to satisfy the Blaschke condition when

:formula_3

Given a sequence obeying the Blaschke condition, the Blaschke product is defined as

:formula_4

with factors

:formula_5

provided formula_6. Here formula_7 is the complex conjugate of formula_8. When formula_9 take formula_10.

The Blaschke product formula_11 defines a function analytic in the open unit disc, and zero exactly at the formula_12 (with multiplicity counted): furthermore it is in the Hardy class formula_13.

The sequence of formula_12 satisfying the convergence criterion above is sometimes called a Blaschke sequence.

==Szegő theorem==

A theorem of Gábor Szegő states that if formula_15, the Hardy space with integrable norm, and if formula_16 is not identically zero, then the zeroes of formula_16 (certainly countable in number) satisfy the Blaschke condition.

==Finite Blaschke products==

Finite Blaschke products can be characterized (as analytic functions on the unit disc) in the following way: Assume that formula_16 is an analytic function on the open unit disc such 
that formula_16 can be extended to a continuous function on the closed unit disc

: formula_20

that maps the unit circle to itself. Then formula_16 is equal to a finite Blaschke product

:formula_22

where formula_23 lies on the unit circle and formula_24 is the multiplicity of the zero formula_25, 
formula_26. In particular, if formula_16 satisfies the condition above and has no zeros inside the unit circle, then formula_16 is constant (this fact is also a consequence of the maximum principle for harmonic functions, applied to the harmonic function formula_29.

